















A Theory of Telic Coherence

David Maurice Garrett























AUTHOR’S PREFACE

This work began as a set of independent investigations into free will, ethics, and rational normativity. Each was motivated by a dissatisfaction with inherited dichotomies that dominate contemporary philosophy: determinism versus indeterminism, objectivity versus relativism, secular rationality versus religious authority. Over time, it became clear that these dichotomies persist not because they are unavoidable, but because they share unexamined assumptions about the structure of reality, agency, and moral responsibility.

The present monograph is an attempt to replace those assumptions with a unified framework. It proceeds from the conviction that metaphysics, moral psychology, ethics, and cultural norm-stabilization cannot be treated as separable domains without distortion. Accounts of free will that ignore ontology collapse into incoherence; ethical systems that ignore agency over-demand or under-demand; moral theories that ignore cultural persistence dissolve under historical pressure.

This work therefore advances a single integrated system whose core claims are modest in ambition but strong in implication. It does not claim to deliver final answers, nor does it rely on revelation, ideological allegiance, or metaphysical excess. Instead, it asks what must be true for reality to be intelligible, for agency to be meaningful, for responsibility to be just, and for moral norms to endure.

The system is developed in four stages, each building on the previous:

    1. A metaphysical account of self-determinism and distributed agency
    2. A constrained and realistic account of moral culpability
    3. A hierarchical model of ethics grounded in capacity and development
    4. A proposal for cultural moral stabilization without supernatural authority

The unifying idea is simple but demanding: that moral normativity is not imposed from outside reality, but emerges from the requirements of coherent existence itself.

Readers will find that this work draws on established philosophical, psychological, and scientific sources, while also engaging with the Cognitive-Theoretic Model of the Universe (CTMU) as a formal metaphysical framework. Acceptance of that framework is not required for engagement with the ethical conclusions, but it does provide the most comprehensive account of self-determinism currently available.

This monograph is offered not as a closed system, but as a structured proposal—one that aims to be internally coherent, externally constrained, and open to refinement. If it succeeds, it will have shown that freedom, responsibility, ethics, and meaning can coexist without contradiction, dogma, or despair.


SYSTEM OVERVIEW

Telic Coherence, Distributed Agency, and Hierarchical Normativity

1. Aim and Scope

This work advances a unified philosophical system integrating metaphysics, free will, ethics, and moral meaning into a single coherent framework. Rather than treating these domains as independently grounded, it argues that they are logically continuous expressions of a common underlying structure of reality.

The central claim is that reality is a self-configuring, self-actualizing system whose continued coherence depends on the participation of internally generated agents. These agents are finite, developmentally stratified, and constrained by circumstance, yet capable of genuine volition. Moral normativity arises not from command or convention, but from alignment with the conditions required for coherent self-actualization across multiple scales of reality.

2. The Telic Coherence Principle

At the core of the system lies the Telic Coherence Principle (TCP):

A system is ontologically stable and morally optimal to the degree that its internal agents act in ways that preserve and enhance coherent self-actualization across local, systemic, and global scales.

This principle grounds moral obligation without appealing to supernatural authority or subjective preference. It explains why certain norms—justice, truthfulness, reciprocity, respect for agency—are not optional, even if they are not universally accessible.

3. Metaphysical Foundation: Self-Determinism

Reality is neither strictly deterministic nor indeterministic. A deterministic universe admits only one possible future and eliminates freedom; an indeterministic universe dissolves agency into randomness. The framework adopted here instead understands reality as self-deterministic: its future states are selected from genuine ontic potential through internally generated criteria.

This structure preserves both openness and authorship. The future is not fixed in advance, yet it is not arbitrary. Agency emerges naturally as a localized expression of this same self-deterministic process.



4. Distributed and Graded Agency

Agency is not binary. Cognitive capacity, motivational structure, developmental maturity, and situational constraint all vary, and moral responsibility varies with them. The system therefore rejects any account of responsibility that treats all agents as equally capable moral actors.

A foundational principle follows:

No agent can be morally culpable for failing to act at a level of ethical abstraction they are structurally incapable of accessing.

This principle underwrites a realistic and just conception of responsibility while preserving moral seriousness.

5. Hierarchical Ethics

Ethical norms must scale with agency. Flat ethical systems either over-demand—condemning agents for failures beyond their capacity—or under-demand, collapsing into relativism. A hierarchical ethical framework avoids both errors by recognizing developmental stratification while preserving a highest normative ideal.

Rule Utilitarianism emerges at this highest level, not as a compromise theory, but as a structural necessity. Stable rules protecting justice and agency are conditions for long-term utility, not exceptions to it.

6. Moral Meaning and Cultural Stability

Ethical systems must persist across generations, power asymmetries, and incentive failures. Historically, religion has provided this stability by sacralizing norms. This work argues that sacredness need not be supernatural. Certain norms must be treated as inviolable because violating them destabilizes the conditions of coherent existence.

A rational moral proto-religion—institutional, fallible, non-coercive—can preserve the stabilizing functions of religion without dogma or authoritarianism.

7. System Integration

The system is articulated across four works:

    1. Telic Triality, Free Will, and the CTMU – metaphysical foundation
(Original paper titled: Telic Triality, Free Will, and the CTMU)

    2. Free Will, First Cause, and Moral Culpability – stratified responsibility
(Original paper titled: Reality, Cognition, and Theodicy)

    3. Hierarchical Ethics – normative structure
(Original paper titled: Hierarchical Ethics)

    4. Intelligent Design, Rationality, and Moral Proto-Religion – cultural stabilization
(Original paper titled: Rational Beings, Intelligent Design, and the Culpability of the First Cause)

Together, they articulate a single claim: that freedom is participatory, responsibility is constrained, ethics is hierarchical, and moral meaning emerges from telic coherence.

































Paper 1. Telic Triality, Free Will, and the CTMU

David M. Garrett

Abstract

In the Cognitive-Theoretic Model of the Universe (CTMU), free will is stratified across a Trialic Metaformal Language of reality:

(1) Globally, the universe self-generates and self-configures, preserving its internal logic in a self-deterministic evolution;

(2) Fundamentally, at the sub-atomic level, the universe self-selects from ontic potential in an act of ongoing actualization; and

(3) Systemically, above the sub-atomic level, the universe generates perceiving entities that possess volition and may participate in alignment or misalignment with global utility.

This paper argues that free will is neither compatible with strict determinism nor rescued by indeterminism, but instead emerges naturally from a self-determining universe whose future remains genuinely open. By explicating the ontological structure required for volition, this work establishes the metaphysical conditions necessary for agency without collapsing into randomness or fatalism.

Systemic Context

This paper establishes the metaphysical conditions for agency assumed by the broader philosophical system developed in subsequent works. In particular, it provides an account of self-determinism, distributed volition, and the openness of the future as required for meaningful freedom. Ethical, normative, and cultural implications are intentionally deferred and addressed in later papers.

1. Free Will and the False Dichotomy

The problem of free will has traditionally been framed as a dilemma between determinism and indeterminism. Determinism holds that the universe’s future is fully fixed by its past in accordance with inviolable laws of nature. If this is the case, then no agent could ever have acted otherwise, and free will collapses into illusion.¹ Indeterminism, by contrast, introduces randomness into the unfolding of events, but randomness cannot ground authorship or responsibility.²

A commonly cited definition of free will is provided by Peter van Inwagen, who characterizes it as the ability of an agent to perform or refrain from performing an action under identical prior conditions.³ Closely related is the concept of volition, the faculty by which an agent selects among possible courses of action using intention rather than reflex or chance.

The persistence of the determinism–indeterminism dichotomy reflects a shared assumption: that causation must be either externally imposed or absent altogether. The Cognitive-Theoretic Model of the Universe (CTMU) rejects this assumption by introducing a third alternative—self-determinism.⁴

2. Self-Determinism and Unbound Telesis

Self-determinism is the property of a system whereby its future states are selected from genuine ontic potential through internally generated criteria rather than imposed external causation or stochastic randomness.

In a self-deterministic universe, the future is genuinely open, not merely unknown. The CTMU characterizes this openness as Unbound Telesis (UBT)—a primordial domain of unconstrained potential from which reality actualizes itself.⁵ UBT is not a probabilistic distribution over pre-existing outcomes, but pre-informational possibility that becomes constrained only through the act of actualization itself.

This structure avoids the pitfalls of both determinism and indeterminism. The universe neither “knows” a unique future in advance nor evolves blindly by chance. Instead, it recursively selects among possible states according to internally defined utility constraints.⁶

3. Trialic Structure of Reality

The CTMU formalizes reality as a Trialic Metaformal Language, consisting of three inseparable but non-reducible levels.

3.1 Global (Macroscopic) Level

At the global level, reality is described by the Global Operator Descriptor (G.O.D.), the maximal self-descriptive operator of the universe as a whole. G.O.D. is not a personal deity but a formal construct denoting reality’s capacity to generate, constrain, and interpret its own informational content.⁷

At this level, reality self-generates from ontic potential through an internally defined teleology, preserving logical coherence across all scales.

3.2 Fundamental (Microscopic) Level

At the quantum level, reality self-selects from ontic potential through telic recursion. This process replaces both classical determinism and stochastic indeterminism with a model in which actualization is guided by utility rather than chance.⁸

The so-called “collapse of the wave function” is thus not an inexplicable anomaly, but an expression of reality’s self-configuration, wherein laws, objects, and states co-emerge through recursive constraint.⁹

3.3 Systemic (Mesoscopic) Level

At the systemic level, reality generates perceiving entities—telors—that inherit constrained volitional capacity. These agents participate locally in the actualization of reality by modeling possible futures and selecting among them through intention and action.¹⁰

4. Volition, Foreknowledge, and Open Futures

For an agent to possess genuine freedom, the future must not already be fixed. Any model that posits a uniquely determined future—whether encoded in physical law or divine foreknowledge—collapses freedom into conformity.¹¹

If an outcome is known with certainty prior to action, then deviation from that outcome is impossible. Foreknowledge of a unique future therefore functions as determinism, regardless of whether it is attributed to God or to the laws of nature.¹²

In contrast, the CTMU posits that reality itself does not possess foreknowledge of a single actualized future. Instead, it evolves from UBT through self-determined actualization, preserving genuine alternatives until selection occurs.

5. Distributed Volition and the Necessity of Agents

Reality must generate agents with volition for a fundamental reason: meaning requires perception. A universe devoid of internal observers would be informationally inert and therefore meaningless. Telors function as self-excited circuits through which reality observes, interprets, and generates itself.¹³

Volition is not granted to agents arbitrarily, nor does it require a break in causality. Instead, it is a localized expression of the same self-deterministic structure operative at the global level.

6. Ordinal Volition and Capacity

Agency is not binary. The CTMU accommodates this by recognizing graded volitional capacity, consistent with ordinal models of agency developed in artificial intelligence and cognitive science.¹⁴

As systems increase in complexity—acquiring memory, feedback, feedforward modeling, self-reference, and teleology—they increasingly participate in self-determination. Human agents occupy the upper ranges of this scale, possessing the capacity to model complex futures, reflect on intentions, and regulate behavior accordingly.

This graded structure of agency will later prove essential for understanding moral responsibility.

7. Self-Determinism and Causation

Free will does not require the breaking of causal chains. Rather, it requires that intention become a causal input within those chains. In self-determined systems, causation is recursive and context-sensitive, incorporating feedback and feedforward loops that allow agents to influence outcomes without violating coherence.¹⁵

Intentional action is therefore neither random nor predetermined, but internally generated within a constrained causal framework.

8. Conclusion and Transition

This account establishes that freedom is neither an illusion nor an exception to causation, but a distributed feature of a self-deterministic universe. Agents possess volition insofar as they participate in telic recursion under constraint, modeling and selecting among genuinely open futures.

What remains to be addressed is not whether such agents are free, but how responsibility should be understood when freedom is real, graded, and developmentally constrained. That question forms the focus of the next stage of this system.


















