GENERAL CONCLUSION

Telic Coherence, Moral Responsibility, and the Conditions of Meaning

This monograph set out to address a cluster of philosophical problems that are often treated independently but, upon closer inspection, resist isolation. Questions about free will, moral responsibility, ethical normativity, and cultural meaning recur across philosophy, theology, and the social sciences precisely because they are not separable. Attempts to resolve any one of them in abstraction tend to generate distortions elsewhere. The central contention of this work has been that these problems admit of a coherent resolution only when treated as expressions of a single underlying structure.

That structure has been articulated in terms of self-determinism and telic coherence. Against the traditional dichotomy between determinism and indeterminism, the system developed here argues that reality is neither a closed causal mechanism nor an arbitrary flux, but a self-configuring process whose future remains genuinely open while internally constrained. Within such a reality, agency is not anomalous but necessary: a universe that must model and actualize itself requires internal loci of perception, intention, and choice.
From this metaphysical foundation, several consequences follow with logical force.

First, free will is real but constrained. Agents possess volition not by standing outside causation, but by participating locally in self-determined processes. This participation is graded rather than binary, varying with cognitive capacity, developmental maturity, and situational constraint. Freedom, on this account, is not the power to transcend all conditions, but the capacity to model alternatives and act intentionally within them.

Second, moral responsibility must therefore be stratified. The long-standing impulse to assign absolute culpability—to human agents or to a First Cause—rests on an idealized conception of agency that no finite system can satisfy. By distinguishing global causal responsibility from local moral culpability, this work has shown that responsibility can be preserved without injustice and that ultimate causation does not entail ultimate blameworthiness. Moral evaluation must scale with genuine access to alternatives, not with abstract metaphysical ideals.

Third, ethical normativity is necessarily hierarchical. Flat ethical systems fail because they either over-demand—condemning agents for failures beyond their capacity—or under-demand, collapsing into relativism or expediency. By integrating motivational psychology, moral development theory, and rule-based consequentialism, this work has argued that ethical expectations must track developmental and situational realities while still converging on a highest normative ideal. That ideal is not arbitrary: it consists in alignment with the conditions required for sustained, coherent existence across individual, social, and global scales.

Finally, moral meaning must be culturally stabilized. Even the most rigorous ethical framework is inert if it cannot persist across generations, power asymmetries, and incentive failures. Historically, religion has fulfilled this stabilizing function by sacralizing norms and embedding them in identity and ritual. The final contribution of this monograph has been to show that sacredness need not be supernatural. Norms may be treated as inviolable not because they are divinely commanded, but because violating them undermines the structural conditions of intelligibility, cooperation, and agency itself.

The resulting proposal—a rational moral proto-religion grounded in telic coherence—does not seek to replace existing religious traditions, nor to impose a new orthodoxy. It offers instead a conceptual framework for understanding why certain norms recur across cultures, why they resist reduction to preference or convention, and why attempts to discard them entirely tend to be self-defeating.

This work does not claim finality. It is offered as a structured proposal rather than a closed system. Its success should be measured not by whether one accepts every metaphysical commitment advanced here, but by whether the framework succeeds in holding together what so often comes apart: freedom without randomness, responsibility without cruelty, ethics without arbitrariness, and meaning without dogma.

If those elements can indeed coexist—as this system argues they must—then moral philosophy need not oscillate between despair and authoritarianism. It may instead proceed with humility, realism, and a renewed sense of purpose grounded not in transcendence beyond reality, but in deeper alignment with reality itself.




















